{"focus":{"id":"0a685ed9-128b-5f60-84ed-f4f0738ae2b6","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d6fe1-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"7.EE.A.2","description":"Understand that rewriting an expression in different forms in a problem context can shed light on the problem and how the quantities in it are related. *For example, $a + 0.05a = 1.05a$ means that \"increase by 5%\" is the same as \"multiply by 1.05.\"*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["7"],"grade":"7","domain":"EE","cluster":"7.EE.A","level":"standard"},"ancestors":[],"descendants":[{"id":"462cc946-7401-513a-a579-65a5d64e7ce9","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c5ae5-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-SSE.A.1","description":"Interpret expressions that represent a quantity in terms of its context","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-SSE","cluster":"HSA-SSE.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"9354b4ae-34f1-5768-9f99-07b5c9292ee4","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba155d1-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-SSE.B.3.a","description":"Factor a quadratic expression to reveal the zeros of the function it defines.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-SSE","cluster":"HSA-SSE.B","level":"substandard"},{"id":"3731426a-99df-53e6-b796-47a194b72f62","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba1d702-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-SSE.B.3.b","description":"Complete the square in a quadratic expression to reveal the maximum or minimum value of the function it defines.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-SSE","cluster":"HSA-SSE.B","level":"substandard"},{"id":"05163bd2-5fa8-58ad-810a-d9d8039062bd","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba237aa-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-SSE.B.3.c","description":"Use the properties of exponents to transform expressions for exponential functions. *For example the expression $1.15^{t}$ can be rewritten as ${(1.15^{\\frac{1}{12}})}^{12t} \\approx 1.012^{12t}$ to reveal the approximate equivalent monthly interest rate if the annual rate is 15%.*","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-SSE","cluster":"HSA-SSE.B","level":"substandard"},{"id":"09ae5d13-9211-58d4-88a2-f42b6d755699","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c54a3-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-CED.A.1","description":"Create equations and inequalities in one variable and use them to solve problems. Include equations arising from linear and quadratic functions, and simple rational and exponential functions.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-CED","cluster":"HSA-CED.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"7bf83ce5-c739-5d93-aef9-fc92540518d5","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d8f41-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-CED.A.2","description":"Create equations in two or more variables to represent relationships between quantities; graph equations on coordinate axes with labels and scales.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-CED","cluster":"HSA-CED.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"ad83f760-4517-5272-a74a-71f8ae9fa783","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e5c5a-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-CED.A.3","description":"Represent constraints by equations or inequalities, and by systems of equations and/or inequalities, and interpret solutions as viable or nonviable options in a modeling context. *For example, represent inequalities describing nutritional and cost constraints on combinations of different foods.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-CED","cluster":"HSA-CED.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"78d6afb1-5683-570f-9e44-8f3a1041b452","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9efd43-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-CED.A.4","description":"Rearrange formulas to highlight a quantity of interest, using the same reasoning as in solving equations. *For example, rearrange Ohm's law $V = IR$ to highlight resistance $R$.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-CED","cluster":"HSA-CED.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"042c432f-410c-5dd9-a87f-e6413634a266","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f97c6-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSF-LE.B.5","description":"Interpret the parameters in a linear or exponential function in terms of a context.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"F-LE","cluster":"HSF-LE.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"f7cc5a71-2d54-5197-9757-3b99d3b468a9","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d8c97-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-APR.B.2","description":"Know and apply the Remainder Theorem: For a polynomial p(x) and a number a, the remainder on division by x - a is p(a), so p(a) = 0 if and only if (x - a) is a factor of p(x).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-APR","cluster":"HSA-APR.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"d7e1d5de-d82c-5489-a1f3-38fc49b7f9b0","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0f6fa-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSN-CN.C.9","description":"(+) Know the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra; show that it is true for quadratic polynomials.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"N-CN","cluster":"HSN-CN.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"897aefc4-aadd-5681-b5cb-20ae995b6dfb","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e5a39-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSA-APR.B.3","description":"Identify zeros of polynomials when suitable factorizations are available, and use the zeros to construct a rough graph of the function defined by the polynomial.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"A-APR","cluster":"HSA-APR.B","level":"standard"}],"learningComponents":[{"id":"75924fc9-b2ad-5273-b21d-e7b8c262153a","description":"Interpret how quantities in an expression are related","author":"Achievement Network","provider":"Learning Commons"},{"id":"41261db0-5e95-5198-ae17-0e905db9ab53","descript